{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641820"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.79,0.13,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72785"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5098"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72785"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following classes of medications have been engineered to evade degradation by DPP-IV?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amylin analogues","GLP-1 analogues","Leptin analogues","CCK analogues","PYY analogues"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLP-1 analogues\u003C/strong\u003E have been engineered to evade degradation by the enzyme dipeptidyl peptidase-IV (DPP-IV). This enzyme rapidly degrades endogenous incretin hormones, including glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), which are important for glucose regulation. By modifying GLP-1 analogues to resist DPP-IV degradation, their half-life is extended, allowing for more effective glycaemic control in patients with type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmylin analogues\u003C/strong\u003E are used to complement insulin therapy by slowing gastric emptying and suppressing glucagon secretion, but they are not specifically engineered to evade DPP-IV degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptin analogues\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in regulating appetite and energy balance, but they are not related to DPP-IV degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECCK analogues\u003C/strong\u003E (cholecystokinin) are involved in digestion and satiety but are not engineered to evade DPP-IV degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPYY analogues\u003C/strong\u003E (peptide YY) are involved in appetite regulation but are not related to DPP-IV degradation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["GLP-1 analogues have been engineered to evade degradation by DPP-IV, enhancing their therapeutic efficacy in managing type 2 diabetes.","DPP-IV is an enzyme that rapidly degrades incretin hormones, including GLP-1, reducing their effectiveness in glucose regulation.","Modifications to GLP-1 analogues increase their half-life, allowing for better glycaemic control in patients."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035Pathak R, Bridgeman MB. Dipeptidyl Peptidase-4 (DPP-4) Inhibitors In the Management of Diabetes. P T. 2010 Sep;35(9):509-13. PMID: 20975810; PMCID: PMC2957740","Gallwitz B. Clinical Use of DPP-4 Inhibitors. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2019 Jun 19;10:389. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2019.00389. PMID: 31275246; PMCID: PMC6593043","Hernando-Redondo J, Toloba A, Benaiges D, Salas-Salvad\u00f3 J, Mart\u00ednez-Gonzalez MA, Corella D, Estruch R, Tinahones FJ, Ros E, Goday A, Casta\u00f1er O, Fit\u00f3 M. Mid- and long-term changes in satiety-related hormones, lipid and glucose metabolism, and inflammation after a Mediterranean diet intervention with the goal of losing weight: A randomized, clinical trial. Front Nutr. 2022 Nov 18;9:950900. doi: 10.3389/fnut.2022.950900. PMID: 36466401; PMCID: PMC9716624","Yeung AY, Tadi P. Physiology, Obesity Neurohormonal Appetite And Satiety Control. 2023 Jan 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310366"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T08:28:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T08:29:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10621"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72785"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical 